    # [Scene: Niko's Boatyard | Dawn, Late Spring]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_1 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Low tide slapping against pilings; distant gulls complaining]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Quiet, rising piano motif; soft percussive taps like hammers]
    "You smell tar and wet rope before you see the faces arriving—neighbors with gloves dusted in mud, Marina Lopez's students in bright rain hats clutching notebooks, old boatwrights with sun-creased forearms. Your notebook is heavy in"
    "your jacket pocket, stuffed with lists, plant surveys, and a crude tally of donations. When you push open the yard's gate, the space exhales: the smell of varnish, coffee, and work."
    "Niko Kaur is already there, elbows caked in mud, signaling a crew toward the shallow reef line. They look up, braid catching the light, and for a second you are both just two people who still remember how to move a keel."
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "You up for directing the sorting? Marina's got two kids who can haul mesh, but they'll need supervision."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "(You laugh, the sound small and steady.) Of course. Someone has to keep them from tangling the net—"

    niko_kaur "—or from convincing you to test the new reef cages on your own.' (Niko smirks, then their face smooths into something softer.) 'Seriously, I mean it. You did the design. You should say how it goes."

    amina_reyes "I will. But we do it together. You know that."
    "The conversation rolls the way it always does here—practical, threaded with warmth. You direct volunteers with the same attention you once reserved for tide charts. You teach Marina Lopez's students how to read the gradient of"
    "the mud: where eelgrass takes hold, where wrack accumulates, where a recruited oyster cluster will anchor. Their eyes light like tiny lanterns when they spot a juvenile crab."
    show marina_lopez at center:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_lopez "You should write that up for the school bulletin. They'll be proud."

    amina_reyes "We will. Take pictures—show them the before and after. They should know what they save."

    marina_lopez "They already do know. They just needed to remember they can help save it."
    "You watch hands, not faces—the way a volunteer lifts a rock to add weight to a cage, the way an elder woman's fingers still bend with the strength of years as she ties rope. It is"
    "slow—far slower than any grant application promised—but every small muscle of progress makes a mark. Progress that tastes faintly of sea-salt and the ache of muscles you didn't know you had."

    menu:
        "Sketch the new strain gauge in your notebook now":
            "You pull the notebook out, page rustling, and draw the tiny instrument with the same reverence you once drew shorelines. The sketch feels like a promise: measuring is caring."
        "Go check the reef cages at low tide first":
            "You fold the notebook back into your jacket and leave it there—some tests require eyes in the muck, not ink on a page. Your boots sink into the mud and you feel, briefly, how alive everything is."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    # [Scene: The Reef Line | Midday; Low Tide Exposure]
    hide niko_kaur
    hide amina_reyes
    hide marina_lopez

    scene bg ch15_3be532_2 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Squelch of boots; the soft clink of metal; seabirds quarrelling]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Gentle strings; a warm, steady rhythm suggesting quiet industry]
    "Fundraising was never a straight line. You learned how to make arguments that read like poems and budgets at the same time: letters to small foundations, a viral post from Marina Lopez that brought in a"
    "trickle, a concert on the boardwalk that paid for another month's materials. The sporadic grants meant timing everything like a tide—one week you had nails and enough cement to set cages; the next week you rationed"
    "rope and used reclaimed planks."
    "Niko Kaur comes back from the water, salt on their shirt, hair threaded with bits of seaweed. They toss you a damp thermos."
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "You know, I used to think grants were for other people—now I write thank-you notes like they're prayers."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "They kind of are.' (You take the thermos; the coffee is bitter in the way that keeps you awake.) 'But thanks to the donations, we bought the stainless mesh. It'll last longer in the water. Your welds held on the east cage—good work."

    niko_kaur "You saw it. You always do.' (They duck their head away, but their smile is soft.) 'And you taught Marina Lopez's kids to spot recruits. I caught one of them teaching the younger ones how to steady a cage."
    "Your chest lightens in that small way that comes from being seen. It isn't the triumph of a ribbon-cutting; it's the steady, human recognition that the work matters—that despite the slow pace, hands that know how to sew, mend, and lift are the infrastructure you trust."
    # [Scene: Boatyard Workshop | Evening]
    hide niko_kaur
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_3 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A steady rasp of a plane on a plank; kettle boiling]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Low cello with an undercurrent of hope]
    "Evening slips over the yard and you find yourself sanding a spar beside Niko Kaur. Your hands go on autopilot—pressure, stroke, rotate—and you notice how calluses fold into new ones. The rhythm is meditative."
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "You ever regret choosing this?"
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "Sometimes. On nights when I try to sleep and I can still hear the boardwalk snapping like thin ice.' (Your fingers pause; you set the sandpaper aside and rub the bridge of your nose.) 'But then I think of the kids on the roof garden pulling seedlings, of Mrs. Alvarez hauling stones at seventy, and I remember why we refused the envelope."

    niko_kaur "You could've taken the appointment. Kenji said—"

    amina_reyes "Kenji said we could get more data if I took the regional position.' (You shrug; the weight of the notebook feels lighter than the thought of leaving.) 'But I kept my name off the lists. I wanted this to be ours. I wanted to keep the craft in our hands."
    "Niko Kaur places a stray curl behind your ear—an action so small it could be a habit. Their braid brushes your shoulder when they lean close to align a spar. The contact is warm and immediate, and for a moment all tides pause."

    menu:
        "Tell Niko you don't regret staying":
            "You say it simply: 'I don't regret it.' It lands between you like a planked bridge—steady and true. They squeeze your hand, and both of you return to work with a new quiet certainty."
        "Tease Niko about their sentimental side":
            "You nudge them with an elbow. 'Since when did Niko Kaur become a poet?' They grin, but their eyes are soft, because they know you mean it. The banter keeps the night from getting heavy."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    # [Scene: Two Months Later — Storm Season Gathering | On the Rooftop Garden]
    hide niko_kaur
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_4 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Wind testing the panels; distant, hollow booms from the sea]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single held violin note that builds into a chord of concern]
    "Storm season arrives early and mean. You sense it before the first rain hits—the air thickens, gulls fly wrong, and the horizon cuts a hard line of possible disaster. The community gathers: tarps, boats, children clinging"
    "to parents. You stand with Marina Lopez and Niko Kaur, maps and lists in hand, errands quick and efficient."
    show marina_lopez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_lopez "We can move the school supplies to the shelter. The kids can help with the lowers—lessons that matter."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "Check the reef anchors again. Tie additional ballast. Niko, double crew on the east line."
    "The rain comes like a verdict. You are on the water when the sky finally splits, the sea thrashing in teeth at the reef cages you and dozens of hands set. You watch from a small"
    "workboat as waves rattle the buoy lines, and you feel a particular cold—an inside chill that says the season means business."
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: A wall of rain; the metallic creak of a failing anchor; a distant cracking noise]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Staccato strings; then a low, sustaining note of loss]
    "By dawn, two of the east cages are gone, along with weeks of seedlings and anchored wrack—months of volunteer sweat dismantled in a handful of hours. You stand on the beach in mud to your ankles, chest heaving more from numbness than exertion."
    show niko_kaur at center:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "We can patch. We can—' (Their voice fractures, then hardens.) 'We can rebuild. It will take longer, but we will do it."

    amina_reyes "We will.' (You taste salt that is not the sea; your throat thickens.) 'We will make them stronger. We'll change the anchors, add a deadweight bed, replant where we can."
    "The loss is brutal. It feels personal, as though the marsh itself scolded you for believing in small miracles. But it also becomes the moment you see how much you have built: the way people return"
    "the next day with hands still tender, with nails and planks and a willingness that isn't granted by contracts."

    marina_lopez "My students cataloged before the storm. The data saved some markers; we have a baseline. That's more than we had before."

    amina_reyes "Then we start from it. We teach them to record what the storm takes, and what survives. Knowledge is a kind of anchor too."
    "You move through the yard like machinery—tired, but purposeful. Niko Kaur and you argue about priorities—mesh purchase, which cages to replace, which beds are vital. The argument is not a rupture; it's the machinery of people who care."

    niko_kaur "If we'd taken that safety envelope, maybe—"

    amina_reyes "Maybe the envelope would have saved some things.' (You do not finish the sentence. The unretractable 'maybe' hangs, complicated.) 'But we'd have lost ownership. We chose the harder route. We chose memory. The choice isn't being punished; it's being tested."

    menu:
        "Stay all night tarping and salvaging":
            "You stay. You wrap yourself in an old sail and hand out hot coffee. The night is long, but by morning you have a new list and more hands than you did the day before."
        "Go home, sleep, and return in the morning":
            "You force yourself to leave. At home you fall asleep in clothes still damp with rain, and you wake with a lump of resolve that feels like muscle—enough to return and rebuild."

    # --- merge ---
    "Narrative continues"
    # [Scene: Boatyard — Weeks After the Storm; Rebuilding]
    hide marina_lopez
    hide amina_reyes
    hide niko_kaur

    scene bg ch15_3be532_5 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Sawing, laughter threaded with fatigue, a radio playing an old sea shanty]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Warm, ascending strings; a piano motif that resolves each phrase with a hopeful cadence]
    "The recovery is slower. Materials must be scavenged, repurposed, bargained for. But you notice the difference between this rebuild and what a top-down project would feel like: every piece of wood carries a story. Mrs. Alvarez's"
    "hammer ring marks a plank that once was part of her porch. A child's name burned into a cleat means future generations know what this place took to be whole."
    "You begin to teach, not as a lecture but as an apprenticeship. Marina Lopez's students learn to measure salinity with a paper straw and a careful eye. You show a pair of new volunteers how to"
    "tie a fisher's knot that won't slip in fast water. Your notebook fills: new protocols, diagrams, lists of who knows what. You keep one section labeled 'stories'—an archive of oral histories the town begins to tell"
    "again on long evenings."
    "Niko Kaur sits beside you as dusk melts. Their braid brushes your shoulder; the contact has settled into a language that needs no translation."
    show niko_kaur at left:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "You ever think about leaving? About taking your skills somewhere bigger?"
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "I thought about it in the quiet months when I couldn't sleep. But then someone would bring back a tray of sandwiches from the shelter, or Marina Lopez would read out a child's survey with proud embarrassment, and I'd feel this—' (You place your hand over your heart.) '—knowing I can actually help here. So I stay."

    niko_kaur "Good. Because I like you here. Also because I need someone who can find the morale in a tide chart."

    amina_reyes "And I need someone who can weld a cage with one hand and listen with the other."
    "The romance that grows between you and Niko Kaur is not a sudden flame but a slow, steady hearth. It is the unglamorous poetry of leaning in after long days, of sharing a thermos of coffee"
    "that tastes sweeter than it should. You sleep on a spare bench in the workshop sometimes, waking to the smell of varnish and the quiet rhythm of Niko Kaur's breathing. Your friendship deepens into a partnership"
    "that looks a lot like work: mutual trust, shared labor, and small nightly rituals."
    # [Scene: Rooftop Community Garden | Late Summer Evening]
    hide niko_kaur
    hide amina_reyes

    scene bg ch15_3be532_6 at full_bg
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soft conversation, the distant boom of a repaired buoy; the scent of grilled fish]
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A warm, triumphant chord; soft chorus underscoring community voices]
    "You decline every regional appointment offered after the storm. Kenji's respectful disappointment is a page in your notebook, folded with gratitude. Instead, you accept invitations that matter: to teach a weekend workshop, to advise a neighboring"
    "town on DIY reef cages, to host a youth tide-reading class on the rooftop. Your influence spreads not because you hold a title, but because you taught people to read the world the way you do."
    show marina_lopez at left:
        zoom 0.7

    marina_lopez "They asked me to speak at the school board today. The parents were—' (She laughs.) '—surprisingly moved. You should be proud. You built a curriculum out of mud and perseverance."
    show amina_reyes at right:
        zoom 0.7

    amina_reyes "We did.' (You glance over at your hands—callused, ink-stained, a map of work.) 'And we'll keep building. Not perfect. Not fast. But ours."
    "You close your notebook finally for the night. The leather has the soft sheen of use; the friendship bracelet tucked into the spine brushes your fingers. You flip through pages: sketches of reef cages, notes from"
    "volunteer days, student drawings, lists of materials, and stories—a town's memory stitched into paper. Your hands, the hands that once trembled at the thought of making a difference, are now sure. They are tools with stories."
    "Niko Kaur comes up the ladder carrying two mugs. The braid brushes your shoulder as they sit close enough that your knees touch."
    show niko_kaur at center:
        zoom 0.7

    niko_kaur "You ever think about the town ten years from now?"

    amina_reyes "I see fewer people in some places, maybe a couple of businesses that couldn't make it. But I also see a handful of kids who know how to read a tide and build a reef cage. I see a roof garden that taught a generation to grow salt-tolerant crops. I see a town that chooses itself."

    niko_kaur "That's enough for me."
    "You feel a steady warmth in your chest—hope not as a bright flare, but as a steady flame that keeps the dark from swallowing the work. The town is smaller, yes, and the marsh is reshaping"
    "itself in ways you mourn, but out of the loss grows craft, memory, and a stubborn generosity that functions like defense. It is imperfect. It is real."
    hide marina_lopez
    hide amina_reyes
    hide niko_kaur

    scene bg ch15_3be532_7 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Resolving, warm chord; a soft choir of strings]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Gentle wind; a gull's distant call]
    "You close your notebook and rub your palms together until the ache dulls. The field notebook is full—more pages than you expected to fill. Your hands carry the story: calluses, ink, and a small scar from"
    "a compressive lift last winter. You keep the friendship bracelet in the spine as a talisman."
    "You do not take the regional appointment. You stay. You teach, mend, and lead in ways that cannot be measured by a title. Love comes in the form of quiet nights in the boatyard, braid brushing"
    "shoulder, shared coffee after long days. The town keeps its stubborn face toward the sea. You carry loss—real and heavy—but the losses are held next to what you have salvaged: community, craft, and the steady, patient"
    "work of healing."

    scene bg ch15_3be532_8 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: A single rising piano motif that settles into a resolved, hopeful chord]
    # play sound "sfx_placeholder"  # [Sound: Soft night sounds; a page turning]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_9 at full_bg
    # play music "music_placeholder"  # [Music: Fade Out]

    scene bg ch15_3be532_10 at full_bg
    "THE END"
    # [GAME END]
    return
